INSERT INTO `citationreferences` VALUES (265,1,1,172,'SOUTH AFRICA|SOUTH AFRICAN',3,'CONSTITUTIONAL COURT','constitutional court',NULL,-1,1,'constitutional court','N'),(265,3,1,199,'UNITED STATES|AMERICAN',1,'SUPREME COURT','supreme court',NULL,-1,10,'supreme court','N'),(265,5,1,84,'INDIA|INDIAN',1,'SUPREME COURT','supreme court',NULL,-1,10,'supreme court','N'),(265,7,2,-1,'IC',15,'European Court of Human Rights','European Court of Human Rights',NULL,-1,10,'European Court of Human Rights','N'),(265,8,3,-1,'TR',1269,'Vienna Convention on the Law of Treaties','Vienna Convention on the Law of Treaties',NULL,1,10,'informed by travaux préparatoires.23 \r [17] Our Constitution was the product of negotiations conducted at the Multi-Party \r Negotiating Process.  The final draft adopted by the forum of the Multi-Party \r Negotiating Process was, with few changes, adopted by Parliament.  The Multi-Party \r Negotiating Process was advised by technical committees, and the reports of these \r committees on the drafts are the equivalent of the travaux préparatoires, relied upon \r by the international tribunals.  Such background material can provide a context for the \r interpretation of the Constitution and, where it serves that purpose, I can see no \r reason why such evidence should be excluded.  The precise nature of the evidence, \r and the purpose for which it may be tendered, will determine the weight to be given \r to it. \r  \r [18] It has been said in respect of the Canadian constitution that: \r  \r                                                  \r      23 Article 32 of the Vienna Convention of Treaties 1969, 8 ILM 679 (1969) permits the use of travaux \r préparatoires for the purpose of interpreting treaties.  For examples of the application of this principle, see Keith \r Cox v Canada, United Nations Committee on Human Rights, Communication No. 539/1993, 3 November 1993, \r at 19, stating: \r  \r Nonetheless, when giving a broad interpretation to any human rights treaty, care must be \r taken not to frustrate or circumvent the ascertainable will of the drafters.  Here the rules of \r interpretation set forth in article 32 of the Vienna Convention on the Law of Treaties help \r us by allowing the use of the travaux préparatoires. \r  \r Ng v Canada, United Nations Committee on Human Rights, Communication No 469/1991, 5 November 1993, at \r 9; Young, James and Webster v United Kingdom (1981) 3 EHRR 20, para. 166; Lithgow v United Kingdom \r (1986) 8 EHRR 329, para. 117; and more generally J.G. STARKE, INTRODUCTION TO INTERNATIONAL LAW 481 \r (10th ed., Butterworths)(1989). \r  \r  11','N'),(265,9,1,172,'SOUTH AFRICA|SOUTH AFRICAN',3,'CONSTITUTIONAL COURT','constitutional court',NULL,-1,14,'constitutional court','N'),(265,10,1,199,'United States|American',528,'Supreme Court','408 U.S. 238',NULL,1,17,' state.  The question is not, however, whether the death sentence is a cruel, \r inhuman or degrading punishment in the ordinary meaning of these words but \r whether it is a cruel, inhuman or degrading punishment within the meaning of section \r 11(2) of our Constitution.35  The accused, who rely on section 11(2) of the \r                                                  \r      34 Furman v. Georgia, 408 U.S. 238, 290 (1972)(Brennan, J., concurring). \r  \r  18 \r      35 This has been the approach of certain of the justices of the United States Supreme Court.  Thus, White, J., \r concurring, who said in Furman v. Georgia, supra note 34, at 312, that \"[T]he imposition and execution of the \r death penalty are obviously cruel in the dictionary sense\", was one of the justices who held in Gregg v Georgia, \r infra','N'),(265,11,1,68,'GEORGIA|GEORGIAN',1,'SUPREME COURT','supreme court',NULL,-1,18,'supreme court','N'),(265,12,1,199,'UNITED STATES|AMERICAN',1,'SUPREME COURT','supreme court',NULL,-1,18,'supreme court','N'),(265,13,1,199,'United States|American',528,'Supreme Court','217 U.S. 349',NULL,1,18,'                            