) per Ngcobo J paras 16 - 21. \r  \r  20','N'),(276,284,1,34,'CANADA|CANADIAN',101,'SUPREME COURT OF CANADA','supreme court of canada',NULL,-1,46,'supreme court of canada','N'),(277,285,1,172,'SOUTH AFRICA|SOUTH AFRICAN',3,'CONSTITUTIONAL COURT','constitutional court',NULL,-1,1,'constitutional court','N'),(277,286,2,-1,'IC',23,'International Criminal Court','International Criminal Court',NULL,5,2,'GOLDSTONE J \r [4] \r [5] \r                                              \r In a verbal note dated 25 November 1996, the embassy of the FRG requested \r the Republic of South Africa to extradite the appellant in order to implement the \r prison sentence and to introduce proceedings against him on a further 15 counts of \r fraud allegedly committed by him in the FRG.  In the verbal note the appellant was \r described as a German citizen.  The note also stated that the FRG was \"prepared to \r extradite persons with similar criminal offences to the Republic of South Africa if \r these persons do not have German citizenship and if German extradition laws are \r satisfied.\"2 \r  \r Extradition is governed by the provisions of the Extradition Act of 19623 (the \r Act).  Section 3(2) of the Act provides for the extradition of persons from South \r Africa to countries with which South Africa has no extradition treaty.4  The FRG is \r such a country.  Before the proceedings can commence, section 3(2) requires the \r consent of the first respondent (the President).  On 30 May 1997 the President \r consented to the appellant’s extradition without being notified that he was no longer a \r citizen of the FRG and had become a South African citizen. \r  \r  \r 2 The courts of the FRG have jurisdiction in respect of criminal offences committed by their citizens outside the \r FRG and under the Constitution of the FRG citizens may not be extradited, save to international criminal \r tribunals and the International Criminal Court. \r 3 Act 67 of 1962. \r 4 Section 3(2) provides as follows: \r “Any person accused or convicted of an extraditable offence committed within the jurisdiction \r of a foreign State which is not a party to an extradition agreement shall be liable to be \r surrendered to such foreign State, if the President has in writing consented to his or her being \r so surrendered.” \r 3','N'),(277,287,2,-1,'IC',23,'International Criminal Court','International Criminal Court',NULL,-1,3,'International Criminal Court','N'),(277,288,1,172,'South Africa|South African',451,'Constitutional Court','2000 (2) SA 825 (CC)',NULL,7,4,'7 Harksen v President of the Republic of South Africa and Others 2000 (2) SA 825 (CC); 2000 (5) BCLR 478 \r (CC) at paras 17 – 18.','N'),(277,289,1,172,'South Africa|South African',451,'Constitutional Court','2000 (2) SA 825 (CC)',NULL,9,4,'t section 3(2) is consistent with the Constitution.7  In consequence the \r appellant abandoned the relief he had sought in respect of that provision of the Act. \r  \r On 11 June 2001 the High Court dismissed the appellant\'s application.8  Having \r been granted a positive certificate in terms of rule 18 of this Court’s rules, the \r  \r 7 Harksen v President of the Republic of South Africa and Others 2000 (2) SA 825 (CC); 2000 (5) BCLR 478 \r (CC) at paras 17 – 18. \r 8 The judgment is reported as Geuking v President of the Republic of South Africa and Others 2002 (1) SA 204 \r (C); 2001 (11) BCLR 1208 (C).  References in this judgment will be to the report in the South African Law \r Reports. \r 5','N'),(277,290,1,172,'SOUTH AFRICA|SOUTH AFRICAN',7,'HIGH COURT','high court',NULL,-1,5,'high court','N'),(277,291,1,172,'SOUTH AFRICA|SOUTH AFRICAN',7,'HIGH COURT','high court',NULL,-1,12,'high court','N'),(277,292,1,172,'South Africa|South African',451,'Constitutional Court','2000 (1) SA 1 (CC)',NULL,26,12,'26 Id at 218 B - D with reference to the decisions of this Court in President of the Republic of South Africa and \r Others v South African Rugby Football Union and Others 2000 (1