f Justice and \r Constitutional Development, Advocates for Transformation and Law Society of South Africa intervening) 2002 \r (5) SA 392 (CC); 2002 (10) BCLR 1092 (CC) para 7, Satchwell v President of the Republic of South Africa and \r Another 2003 (4) SA 266 (CC) para 6. \r 2','N'),(281,334,1,172,'SOUTH AFRICA|SOUTH AFRICAN',3,'CONSTITUTIONAL COURT','constitutional court',NULL,-1,1,'constitutional court','N'),(281,335,1,172,'SOUTH AFRICA|SOUTH AFRICAN',7,'HIGH COURT','high court',NULL,-1,2,'high court','N'),(281,336,1,208,'ZIMBABWE|ZIMBABWEAN',7,'HIGH COURT','high court',NULL,-1,2,'high court','N'),(281,341,1,172,'SOUTH AFRICA|SOUTH AFRICAN',7,'HIGH COURT','high court',NULL,-1,4,'high court','N'),(281,342,2,-1,'IC',21,'International Court of Arbitration of the International Chamber of Commerce','International Court of Arbitration of the International Chamber of Commerce',NULL,-1,7,'International Court of Arbitration of the International Chamber of Commerce','N'),(281,343,1,208,'ZIMBABWE|ZIMBABWEAN',7,'HIGH COURT','high court',NULL,-1,8,'high court','N'),(281,344,1,172,'South Africa|South African',451,'Constitutional Court','1998 (4) SA 1157 (CC)',NULL,11,9,'n they face \r there, as well as the possibility of their being extradited to Equatorial Guinea to face \r charges which could result, if they were to be convicted, in their being sentenced to \r death.  These issues involve the reach of the Constitution, and the relationship \r  \r 2 Member of the Executive Council for Development Planning and Local Government, Gauteng v Democratic \r Party and Others 1998 (4) SA 1157 (CC); 1998 (7) BCLR 855 (CC) at para 32. \r 10','N'),(281,345,2,-1,'IC',22,'International Court of Justice','ICJ',NULL,13,11,'CHASKALSON CJ \r states, in this case Zimbabwe and Equatorial Guinea, and on the other, the nature and \r extent of its obligations to citizens beyond its borders.  To answer the questions raised \r it is necessary to deal both with international law and domestic law.  As the setting is \r international, I begin with international law. \r  \r International law \r [23] \r                                              \r Section 232 of the Constitution provides that: \r  \r “Customary international law is law in the Republic unless it is inconsistent with the \r Constitution or an Act of Parliament.” \r  \r Traditionally, international law has acknowledged that states have the right to protect \r their nationals beyond their borders but are under no obligation to do so.  Counsel for \r the government, citing the Barcelona Traction case,3 relied on this principle to support \r the government’s contention that the applicants’ claims are misconceived.  They \r referred to the following passages from the judgment of the International Court of \r Justice (ICJ) in that case: \r  \r “The Court would here observe that, within the limits prescribed by international law, \r a State may exercise diplomatic protection by whatever means and to whatever extent \r it thinks fit, for it is its own right that the State is asserting.  Should the natural or \r legal persons on whose behalf it is acting consider that their rights are not adequately \r protected, they have no remedy in international law.  All they can do is resort to \r municipal law, if means are available, with a view to furthering their cause or \r obtaining redress . . .  \r  \r  \r 3 Barcelona Traction Light and Power Company Limited 1970 ICJ Reports 3; 46 ILR 178. \r 12','N'),(281,346,2,-1,'IC',22,'International Court of Justice','International Court of Justice',NULL,-1,12,'International Court of Justice','N'),(281,348,4,-1,'SL',11,'International Law Commission','ILC',NULL,15,13,'CHASKALSON CJ \r [26] \r [27] \r                                              \r The term diplomatic protection is not a precise term of art.  It is defined in the \r Special Rapporteur’s report as \r  \r “action taken by a State against another State in respect of an injury to the person or \r property of a national caused by an internationally wrongful act or omission \r attributable to the latter State.”6\r  \r It is also used by some commentators to refer to \r  \r “preventing some threatened injury in violation of international law, or of obtaining \r redress for such injuries after they have been sustained.”7\r  \r It appears from the ILC report, however, that there are differences on this and that \r some commentators take the view that diplomatic protection applies only to actions \r taken to secure redress for injuries actually caused.8\r  \r According to the Special Rapporteur’s report, diplomatic protection includes, in \r a broad sense, “consular action, negotiation, mediation, judicial and arbitral \r proceedings, reprisals, retorsion, severance of diplomatic relations, [and] economic \r pressures”.9  Some authorities distinguish between diplomatic action taken by a state \r to secure redress for an injury to a national, and judicial proceedings taken to that end.  \r The distinction is not relevant for the purposes of this case. \r  \r 6 Special Rapporteur’s report above n 5 at 11. \r 7 Dunn The Protection of Nationals: A Study in the Application of International Law (Johns Hopkins Press, \r Baltimore 1932) at 18. \r 8 ILC report above n 5 at 146. \r 9 Special Rapporteur’s report above n 5 at 15. \r 14','N'),(281,349,4,-1,'SL',11,'International Law Commission','ILC',NULL,16,14,'CHASKALSON CJ \r  \r [28] \r [29] \r [30] \r                                              \r It had been suggested that the traditional approach to diplomatic protection, \r such as that set out in the Barcelona Traction case,10 should be developed to recognise \r that in certain circumstances where injury is the result of a grave breach of a jus \r cogens norm, the state whose national has been injured, should have a legal duty to \r exercise diplomatic protection on behalf of the injured person.  As a corollary to that, \r states would be obliged to make provision in their munici