ers \r conventional and less conventional rights in detail.  A right to diplomatic protection is \r a most unusual right, which one would expect to be spelt out expressly rather than \r being left to implication.17 \r  \r Extraterritoriality: the constitutional text \r The starting point of the enquiry into extraterritoriality is to determine the ambit \r of the rights that are the subject matter of section 7(2).  To begin with two \r observations are called for.  First, the Constitution provides the framework for the \r governance of South Africa.  In that respect it is territorially bound and has no \r application beyond our borders.  Secondly, the rights in the Bill of Rights on which \r  \r 14 International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights adopted and opened for signature, ratification and \r accession by the General Assembly of the United Nations, resolution 2200 (XXI) of 16 December 1966.  Entry \r into force: 23 March 1976. \r 15 1996 (2) SA 751 (CC); 1996 (4) BCLR 449 (CC). \r 16 Id at para 106. \r 17 Cf Du Plessis and Others v De Klerk and Another 1996 (3) SA 850 (CC); 1996 (5) BCLR 658 (CC) at para \r 45. \r 18','N'),(281,358,2,-1,'IC',22,'International Court of Justice','ICJ',NULL,29,20,'CHASKALSON CJ \r prohibiting the action concerned.  As Shaw notes, however, two later judgments of the \r ICJ indicate that “the emphasis lies the other way around.”25 \r  \r [40] \r [41] \r [42] \r                                              \r It is not necessary to enter this controversy.  What seems to be clear is that \r when the application of a national law would infringe the sovereignty of another state, \r that would ordinarily be inconsistent with and not sanctioned by international law. \r  \r In the case of R v Cook,26 the majority of the Supreme Court of Canada \r endorsed this understanding of the international law position holding that “the \r principle of the sovereign equality of states generally prohibits extraterritorial \r application of domesti