 of \r law and an independent judiciary, the findings and conclusions of the mission \r included the following: \r  \r • The executive exercises considerable control over both the legislature and the \r judiciary. \r • There is no separation of powers and very little or no respect for the rule of \r law.  Torture, failure to guarantee the right to a fair trial, lack of freedom of \r expression and association, poor prison conditions and the failure of the \r 54','N'),(281,381,4,-1,'SL',9,'Human Rights Committee','Human Rights Committee',NULL,77,54,'CHASKALSON CJ \r judiciary to act independently are some of the examples of human rights abuses \r that occur with impunity. \r • The lack of independence of the judiciary, the expectation that judges will be \r loyal to the government, and the use of military judges in civilian courts are \r cause for concern. \r  \r [122] \r [123] \r                                              \r The South African government says that it is not its policy to comment on the \r justice systems of foreign countries and it has declined to do so.  It takes the attitude \r that the reports are not admissible in evidence and that the court cannot make a \r finding on the efficacy and fairness of the legal and judicial systems of Equatorial \r Guinea without the benefit of expert evidence. \r  \r Its attitude, as expressed in the answering affidavit, is that a decision as to \r whether or not to intervene is one that will be taken by a responsible authority in \r South Africa should the applicants be extradited to Equatorial Guinea.  Whilst this \r Court cannot and should not make a finding as to the present position in Equatorial \r Guinea on the basis only of these reports, it cannot ignore the seriousness of the \r allegations that have been made.  They are reports of investigations conducted by \r reputable international organisations and a Special Rapporteur appointed by the \r United Nations Human Rights Committee.  The fact that such in